{{Refimprove|date=July 2009}} 
'''Rosen Method Bodywork''' (or '''Rosen Method''') is a type of [[Complementary and alternative medicine]].  This [[Bodywork (alternative medicine)|bodywork]], described as "psycho-somatic", claims to help integrate one's bodily and emotional/mental experience while identifying unconscious patterns of muscular holding, feeling, and behavior.<ref>{{cite book |first= Lynn |last= Keegan |year= 2000 |title= Healing with Complementary & Alternative Therapies |publisher= [[Cengage Learning]] |page= [https://books.google.com/books?id=JF5STWO2qtQC&pg=PA195 195] |isbn= 9780766818903}}</ref> The main theory underpinning this method is that a person protects themselves from past painful experiences through the body, separating one from one's [[true self]].<ref name="Raso1997"/> This alleged protection is said to be experienced most frequently as chronic musculoskeletal pain and tension, and purportedly can be observed by the bodywork practitioners as restricted patterns of movement and posture, muscular tension, or shortness of breath.<ref name="Raso1997"/> Rosen Method Bodywork purports to integrate the body, mind, emotions and spirit; and unlock the unconscious.<ref name="Raso1997"/>

[[Quackwatch]] categorized the Rosen Method as an "unnaturalistic method" and says that it features "non-intrusive" touch, verbal interaction, and experiencing breath as "gateway to awareness".<ref name="Raso1997">{{cite book |url= http://www.quackwatch.com/01QuackeryRelatedTopics/dictionary/mdqr.html |title= The Expanded Dictionary of Metaphysical Healthcare, Alternative Medicine, Paranormal Healing, and Related Methods |edition= online |year= 1997 |chapter= Unnaturalistic Methods: QR |last= Raso |first= Jack |publisher= [[Quackwatch]] |accessdate= 2013-10-28}}</ref>

Rosen Method bodywork has developed through its founder [[Marion Rosen]]'s physical therapy practice and work with Lucy Heyer, a student of [[Elsa Gindler]].<ref>{{cite book |first= Douglas |last= Wengell |year= 2008 |title= Educational Opportunities in Integrative Medicine |publisher= The Hunter Press |page= [https://books.google.com/books?id=BNR1KGJXX9cC&pg=PA108 108] |isbn= 9780977655243}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor-first= Nancy |editor-last= Allison |year= 1999 |title= The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Body-mind Disciplines |publisher= [[Rosen Publishing]] |pages= [https://books.google.com/books?id=5199jcnbqwEC&pg=PA16 168–72]}}</ref>

